The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, June 25, 2004 				 Govt okays OVLs Sudan project
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, June 24: The government today approved Oil and Natural Gas Corporations (ONGC) $200-million project to set up an oil pipeline in Sudan.																								ONGC Videsh Ltd (OVL), the overseas investment arm of ONGC, which holds stakes in oil and gas projects in Sudan, Russia and Vietnam, would build and transfer a 741-kilometre petroleum product pipeline from the Khartoum refinery to Port Sudan on the Red Sea.																								The Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs (CCEA) today cleared the signing of the pact with Sudan, which had given the contract for laying the product pipeline and a refinery revamp to India on a nomination basis, oil minister Mani Shankar Aiyar told reporters after the meeting.																								ONGC Videsh, which also has interests in exploration blocks in Iran, Myanmar, Iraq, Libya and Syria, would increase the capacity of the Khartoum refinery to 1 lakh barrels a day from 25,000 barrels.																								The pipeline, which would be part-owned by Indian Oil Corporation and Oil India Ltd, will transport around 50,000 barrels per day from the Khartoum refinery to Port Sudan and is expected to be operational in a year. 
